{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17538885","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17538885"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:34:00+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:34:00+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16401"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16401","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16401"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.06,0.76,0.12,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9092"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102233"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9092","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9092"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16401"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84697"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1196"},{"type":"tags","id":"1367"},{"type":"tags","id":"4111"},{"type":"tags","id":"4148"},{"type":"tags","id":"4983"},{"type":"tags","id":"11643"},{"type":"tags","id":"12798"},{"type":"tags","id":"12801"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21597"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35401"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35402"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43631"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102233","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/102233"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 14-year-old girl presents to the General Practice clinic requesting oral contraception. She reports being in a relationship with a 15-year-old boy from her school for the past six months. She has not had sexual intercourse yet but is considering it. She specifically requests that her parents not be informed. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Provide informed consent","Assess competence under the mental capacity act","Assess Gillick competence","Prescribe oral contraceptive immediately","Inform her parents immediately"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis scenario presents an important ethical and legal situation involving adolescent reproductive healthcare. The key consideration is determining whether the young person has the capacity to consent to medical treatment without parental involvement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAssess Gillick competence\u003C/strong\u003E is the crucial first step in managing this situation. This involves determining whether the young person has sufficient maturity and intelligence to understand fully what is proposed, including the risks and benefits of treatment, alternatives, and implications of their choices. The patient must be able to understand, retain, and weigh up the information to make a decision.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInform her parents immediately\u003C/strong\u003E would breach patient confidentiality if the young person is deemed Gillick competent. Healthcare providers have a duty of confidentiality to all patients, including those under 16, if they are assessed as having capacity to consent.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProvide informed consent\u003C/strong\u003E is not the correct approach as the process of informed consent presupposes capacity, which must first be established in a minor through assessment of Gillick competence.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAssess competence under the mental capacity act\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate in this context. The Mental Capacity Act generally applies to people aged 16 and over, whereas Gillick competence is the relevant framework for assessing capacity in those under 16 years of age.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrescribe oral contraceptive immediately\u003C/strong\u003E without first assessing competence would be inappropriate. A thorough assessment of understanding, capacity, and medical suitability must precede any prescription.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter establishing Gillick competence, the healthcare provider should take a detailed medical history, discuss contraceptive options, perform relevant examinations if indicated, and provide comprehensive counselling about sexual health, including sexually transmitted infections and the importance of safe sex practices.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Assessment of Gillick competence is essential before providing contraception to patients under 16 years of age.","Gillick competence requires that the young person understands the advice given, its implications, and has sufficient maturity to understand what is involved.","Confidentiality should be maintained for Gillick-competent young people, even from their parents, unless there are safeguarding concerns."],"references":["Griffith R. What is Gillick competence? Hum Vaccin Immunother. 2016;12(1):244-7. doi: 10.1080/21645515.2015.1091548. PMID: 26619366; PMCID: PMC4962726."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84697"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16401"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84697","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/84697"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-10T22:07:57+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-11T08:18:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9092"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102233"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"1196","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/1196"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Routine health check","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2021-07-31T02:17:10+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-11T11:05:15+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"3"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"1367","links":{"self":"https://app.